<h1>Microformats</h1>

<p><em>Meaningful HTML</em></p>

<h2 id="what">What are Microformats?</h2>

<p>Microformats are a simple way to add more meaning to you HTML.</p>

<h2 id="how">How to use Microformats?</h2>

<p>
  This snippet of HTML is very common.
  While you as a human can recognize that is contact information,
  computers could use a few hints to understand it.
</p>

<pre><code class="html">&lt;div&gt;
  Emma Goldman&lt;br&gt;
  123 Main St&lt;br&gt;
  Some Town, CA&lt;br&gt;
  90210

  &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:emma.goldman@example.com&quot;&gt;emma.goldman@example.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/emmagoldman&quot;&gt;@emmagoldman&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>


<p>
  By adding just a few HTML classes, you can turn this generic markup into
  much more meaningful and semantic HTML.
</p>

<pre><code class="html">&lt;div class=&quot;h-card&quot;&gt;
  &lt;span class=&quot;p-name&quot;&gt;Emma Goldman&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class=&quot;p-street-address&quot;&gt;123 Main St&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class=&quot;p-locality&quot;&gt;Some Town&lt;/span&gt;, &lt;span clas=&quot;p-region&quot;&gt;CA&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span=&quot;p-postal-code&quot;&gt;90210&lt;/span=&quot;p-postal-code&quot;&gt;

  &lt;a class=&quot;u-email&quot; href=&quot;mailto:emma.goldman@example.com&quot;&gt;emma.goldman@example.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;a class=&quot;u-url&quot; rel=&quot;me&quot; href=&quot;https://twitter.com/emmagoldman&quot;&gt;@emmagoldman&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>


<p>Or an even simpler example is just link.</p>

<pre><code class="html">&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/emmagoldman&quot;&gt;@emmagoldman&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>


<p>All it needs is one <code>h-card</code> class on the link tag.</p>

<pre><code class="html">&lt;a class=&quot;h-card&quot; href=&quot;https://twitter.com/emmagoldman&quot;&gt;@emmagoldman&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>


<h2 id="why">Why use Microformats?</h2>

<p>
  By adding Microformats to your HTML, your website becomes more
  understandable to various kinds of computers.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Search engines can make sense of your HTML which allows them to display a better version in their search results.</li>
  <li>Browser extensions can enable your readers to download information to their contacts, calendar, and maps apps.</li>
  <li>Feed readers can be used to subscribe to your website&rsquo;s feeds (blog posts, bookmarks, checkins, etc).</li>
  <li>You can even use your website (with Microformats) to sign into other websites.</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="what-else">What else are they good for?</h2>

<p>
  In addition to <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-card">people and organizations</a>,
  Microformats can be used for:
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-feed">feeds</a>,
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-entry">blog posts</a>,
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-event">events</a>,
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-adr">locations</a>,
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-review">reviews</a>,
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-recipe">recipes</a>,
  <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-resume">resumes</a>,
  and <a href="http://microformats.org/wiki/h-product">products</a>.
</p>

